<br>
That being said what Hawkestone was involved in was wrong.  The attitude of the guild after the incident is even more messed up.  And every time I turn around there is a new excuse for why it was OK that they did it.<br>
<br>
The bottom line is you were either part of the incident directly or are supporting it indirectly.  You can rationalize till the cows come home about how the &quot;loots better now&quot;, &quot;it was time for him to be released&quot;, so and so (I have heard various groups of players or guilds listed) was going to release him so we did it first (this one always confuses me, just because player X is gonna be an ass does not mean you should), it was our &quot;right&quot; to do it (as if just because you have the right to do something that makes it appropriate) or my favorite, &quot;its just a game&quot; (well if its just a game asshole why not leave him up for the rest of us to enjoy).  None of these holds weight as an excuse alone and together they become an obvious attempt to rationalize poor behavior.<br>
<br>
I imagine that almost everyone on the server would have loved to have awaken the Sleeper or have been part of the event.  But the rest of the server excluding Hawkestone had more foresight or was less self-centered about it.<br>
<br>
I had a friend at work who did something very out of character and really screwed up.  After the incident he rationalized how he was hero and everyone else involved missunderstood what had occurred.  It was incredibly difficult for him to accept what he had done because it was counter to how he veiwed himself.  This was very frustrateing for those of us who worked around him.  Some co-workers, who otherwise would have forgiven him, still resent him because of his refusal to accept responisbility and show that he has learned from his mistakes.<br>
<br>
I sort of see the decent people in Hawkestone as being in this boat albeit in a much less catasrophic way.  They have made a mistake and are now faced with accepting responsibility for screwing up and moving on, or taking the much easier road of rationalizeing what occurred.  Ultimately EQ is just a game and the stakes are no where near as high as real life.  But, it still leaves a sour taste in ones mouth to hear the cries of protest from Hawkestone members when in fact everything that is occurring should have been easily foreseen prior to awakening the Sleeper.  And as Shamu said earlier a simple, &quot;hey we really screwed up&quot; could have solved or at least hugely mitigated the problems most of us are having with Hawkestone.<br>
<br>
I respected many of the members of Hawkestone and am sorry for what they are going through.  I have made numerous mistakes as player and understand that sometimes in the heat of the moment those mistakes are easy to make.  But what is occuring now is a result of their choices, actions and inactions.  Everyone is going to make their own choices about how to handle the incident.  For me, a simple &quot;I'm sorry&quot; followed by remove guild from Hawkestone, and its over (atleast where most of the members are concerned). <br>
